Event: Also, why are paracetamol so hard to swallow? Even when the long ones are snapped in half. Ow.
Post:
"I can't believe I got kicked out of the bar for just having a little too much fun. Maybe I should take it as a sign that I need to work on my drinking habits."

The paracetamol tablets are hard to swallow because they have a large size and are designed to be slow-release, which means they dissolve slowly in the stomach and provide long-lasting pain relief. However, this also makes them difficult to swallow, especially when they are snapped in half. This is because the broken tablet can still be quite large and difficult to get down the throat, causing discomfort or even pain. Additionally, some people may have difficulty swallowing pills in general, which can make it even harder to take paracetamol.
